# Network Intrusion Detection and Prevention System (NIDPS) Using Snort 3

## Abstract

With the rapid growth of computer networks and internet-based services, protecting network infrastructure from cyber threats has become increasingly important. A Network Intrusion Detection and Prevention System (NIDPS) helps identify malicious network activities and prevent attacks before they compromise the system. This project implements a Network Intrusion Detection and Prevention System using Snort 3 on Ubuntu Linux. Snort operates in both Intrusion Detection System (IDS) and Intrusion Prevention System (IPS) modes to monitor network traffic, detect suspicious activities, and block malicious packets. Custom Snort rules were created to detect ICMP ping traffic and TCP SYN scan attacks while preventing unauthorized ICMP traffic in inline mode using AFPacket. The implementation was successfully tested using Kali Linux and Nmap, demonstrating real-time detection and prevention capabilities.

---

# Chapter 1: Introduction

Network security is one of the most critical aspects of modern computing systems. Organizations rely heavily on secure communication networks for business operations, making them attractive targets for cyber attackers. Traditional firewalls are effective at filtering traffic based on predefined policies but cannot always detect sophisticated attacks or abnormal network behavior.

A Network Intrusion Detection and Prevention System (NIDPS) provides an additional layer of security by continuously monitoring network traffic, detecting malicious activities, generating alerts, and preventing attacks. Snort 3 is a widely used open-source NIDPS capable of performing both detection and prevention using signature-based rules.

This project demonstrates the practical implementation of Snort 3 to detect and prevent common network attacks.

